Below is a zero-overhead-in-compute_all() way to support 3 penalty types per constraint:

"simple_penalty" → w * v² (what you have now)

"barrier_penalty-exp" → w * (exp(k*v) - 1)

"barrier_penalty-log" → w * log1p(k*v)

✅ Key property: compute_all() does no string compares and no switch.
Penalty selection is done once during parsing/config init by setting a function pointer inside each ConstraintConfig. In compute_all() it’s just penalty += cfg_.overlap_c.penalty(overlap_pen);.

CHANGE 1 — Replace class ConstraintConfig (adds penalty function pointer + type selection)
Replace this exact code block:
class ConstraintConfig{
public:
	ConstraintConfig() : enabled(false), weight(0.0), normalization("no norm"), aggregation("sum") {}
	bool enabled;
	double weight;
	std::string normalization;
	std::string aggregation;
	std::string type;
};

With this exact code block:
class ConstraintConfig{
public:
  typedef double (*PenaltyFn)(double v, double w, double k);

  ConstraintConfig()
  : enabled(false),
    weight(0.0),
    normalization("no norm"),
    aggregation("sum"),
    type("simple_penalty"),
    barrier_k(1.0),
    penalty_fn_(&ConstraintConfig::SimplePenalty)
  {}

  bool enabled;
  double weight;                 // parsed from "penalty_weight" (or "weight" fallback)
  std::string normalization;
  std::string aggregation;
  std::string type;              // "simple_penalty" | "barrier_penalty-exp" | "barrier_penalty-log"

  // Optional scaling for barrier penalties (default 1.0). If you don't want it, keep default.
  double barrier_k;

  // Set once during parsing/init. NEVER call in compute_all().
  void SetPenaltyType(const std::string& t)
  {
    type = t;
    if (t == "simple_penalty")        penalty_fn_ = &ConstraintConfig::SimplePenalty;
    else if (t == "barrier_penalty-exp") penalty_fn_ = &ConstraintConfig::BarrierPenaltyExp;
    else if (t == "barrier_penalty-log") penalty_fn_ = &ConstraintConfig::BarrierPenaltyLog;
    else throw std::runtime_error("Unknown constraint penalty type: " + t);
  }

  // Fast: one indirect call, no selection/branching on type inside compute_all().
  inline double penalty(const double v) const
  {
    return penalty_fn_(v, weight, barrier_k);
  }

private:
  PenaltyFn penalty_fn_;

  static double SimplePenalty(const double v, const double w, const double /*k*/)
  {
    return w * v * v;
  }

  static double BarrierPenaltyExp(const double v, const double w, const double k)
  {
    // 0 at v=0, grows rapidly. Clamp to prevent inf/NaNs.
    double t = k * v;
    if (t > 50.0) t = 50.0;
    return w * (std::exp(t) - 1.0);
  }

  static double BarrierPenaltyLog(const double v, const double w, const double k)
  {
    // 0 at v=0, always finite; slower growth than exp.
    const double t = std::max(0.0, k * v);
    return w * std::log1p(t);
  }
};

CHANGE 2 — Json parsing: Replace JsonIO::ParseConstraint(...) (proper parsing + penalty type selection)

You didn’t paste your JsonIO code, so I’m giving an exact replace block for the function that parses a constraint node.

Find your existing function that looks like (or is very close to) this:
static ConstraintConfig ParseConstraint(const json& cnode)
{
  ConstraintConfig cc;
  cc.enabled = ParseBoolString(cnode.at("switch").get<std::string>());
  cc.weight = cnode.at("weight").get<double>();
  cc.normalization = cnode.at("normalization").get<std::string>();
  cc.aggregation = cnode.at("aggregation").get<std::string>();
  return cc;
}

Replace that entire function with this exact function:
static ConstraintConfig ParseConstraint(const json& cnode)
{
  ConstraintConfig cc;

  // enabled can come as "enabled" or legacy "switch"
  if (cnode.contains("enabled"))      cc.enabled = ParseBoolString(cnode.at("enabled").get<std::string>());
  else if (cnode.contains("switch"))  cc.enabled = ParseBoolString(cnode.at("switch").get<std::string>());
  else                                cc.enabled = false;

  // penalty weight can come as "penalty_weight" or legacy "weight"
  if (cnode.contains("penalty_weight")) cc.weight = cnode.at("penalty_weight").get<double>();
  else if (cnode.contains("weight"))    cc.weight = cnode.at("weight").get<double>();
  else                                  cc.weight = 0.0;

  if (cnode.contains("normalization")) cc.normalization = cnode.at("normalization").get<std::string>();
  else                                 cc.normalization = "no norm";

  if (cnode.contains("aggregation"))   cc.aggregation = cnode.at("aggregation").get<std::string>();
  else                                 cc.aggregation = "sum";

  // penalty type
  std::string t = "simple_penalty";
  if (cnode.contains("type")) t = cnode.at("type").get<std::string>();
  cc.SetPenaltyType(t);

  // optional parameter for barrier scaling
  if (cnode.contains("barrier_k")) cc.barrier_k = cnode.at("barrier_k").get<double>();

  return cc;
}


✅ This correctly parses your jPars format:

"type" : "simple_penalty",
"penalty_weight" : 100.0


…and supports the two new types.

CHANGE 3 — Replace penalty composition inside LayoutEvaluator::compute_all(...)
Find this exact block in compute_all():
double penalty = 0.0;
if(cfg_.overlap_c.enabled) penalty += cfg_.overlap_c.weight * overlap_pen * overlap_pen;
if(cfg_.boundary_c.enabled) penalty += cfg_.boundary_c.weight * boundary_agg * boundary_agg;
if(cfg_.aspect_c.enabled) penalty += cfg_.aspect_c.weight * aspect_vi * aspect_vi;

Replace it with this exact block:
double penalty = 0.0;

// No selection here. Type is pre-bound via function pointer in ConstraintConfig.
if (cfg_.overlap_c.enabled)   penalty += cfg_.overlap_c.penalty(overlap_pen);
if (cfg_.boundary_c.enabled)  penalty += cfg_.boundary_c.penalty(boundary_agg);
if (cfg_.aspect_c.enabled)    penalty += cfg_.aspect_c.penalty(aspect_vi);


That’s the whole point: compute_all() stays fast and clean.

CHANGE 4 — Ensure parsing calls your updated ParseConstraint

Wherever you parse constraints, you should already have something like:

cfg.overlap_c  = ParseConstraint(c.at("overlap"));
cfg.aspect_c   = ParseConstraint(c.at("aspect_violation"));
cfg.boundary_c = ParseConstraint(c.at("boundary_violation"));


If your current JsonIO uses different names, keep your existing mapping, but ensure each one calls the new ParseConstraint.

No other changes are needed.

How to use in JSON (examples)
Existing behavior (same as now)
"type": "simple_penalty"

Exponential barrier
"type": "barrier_penalty-exp",
"barrier_k": 2.0

Log barrier (soft barrier)
"type": "barrier_penalty-log",
"barrier_k": 5.0


If you omit barrier_k, it defaults to 1.0.

Why this meets your “NO overhead / extremely fast” requirement

No string compares, no switch, no std::function, no virtual calls inside compute_all().

Each constraint penalty is exactly one indirect call (3 calls max per evaluation), which is negligible compared to overlap/bbox calculations.

All selection happens once during parsing/config init.











